Labeled Tuples

Labeled tuples (TypeScript 4.0+) allow naming each element position for better documentation and IntelliSense.

### Syntax

```typescript
type Range = [start: number, end: number];
type HttpResponse = [statusCode: number, body: string, headers?: Record<string, string>];

const response: HttpResponse = [200, "{\"ok\": true}"];
```

### Benefits

Labels improve readability and provide meaningful names in editor tooltips:

```typescript
type GraphPoint = [x: number, y: number, label?: string];

function plotPoint(point: GraphPoint): void {
  const [x, y, label] = point;
  console.log(`Point at (${x}, ${y})${label ? `: ${label}` : ""}`);
}
```

### Labeled Tuples in Functions

```typescript
function createUser(
  ...args: [name: string, age: number, email?: string]
): object {
  const [name, age, email] = args;
  return { name, age, email };
}

createUser("Alice", 30);
createUser("Bob", 25, "bob@example.com");
```

### Mixed Labeled and Unlabeled

```typescript
type CsvLine = [id: number, ...string[]];

const line: CsvLine = [1, "Alice", "alice@example.com", "active"];
```

### Destructuring with Labels

```typescript
type Point = [x: number, y: number, z?: number];

function move([x, y]: Point, dx: number, dy: number): Point {
  return [x + dx, y + dy];
}
```

> **Key Point:** Labels do not affect type compatibility — they exist purely for documentation.

codeExample:
// API response tuple with labels
type ApiResult<T> = [error: Error | null, data: T | null, status: number];

function fetchUser(id: number): ApiResult<{ name: string }> {
  try {
    const user = { name: "Alice" };
    return [null, user, 200];
  } catch (err) {
    return [err as Error, null, 500];
  }
}

const [err, user, status] = fetchUser(1);
if (err) {
  console.error(`Error ${status}:`, err);
} else {
  console.log(user?.name);
}
